  "rules": {
    "Scale.0001": {
      "id": "Scale.0001",
      "description": "Static content detected.\n\nYour current approach of serving static content directly might lead to increased costs, performance issues, maintenance challenges (requiring application redeployment for content changes), and security risks.\n\nConsider moving static content to Azure Blob Storage and adding Azure CDN.",
      "label": "Static content detected",
      "severity": "Optional",
      "effort": 3,
      "links": [
        {
          "title": "Azure Blob Storage",
          "url": "https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?linkid=2250574"
        },
        {
          "title": "Azure CDN",
          "url": "https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?linkid=2250392"
        }
      ]
    },
    "Connection.0001": {
      "id": "Connection.0001",
      "description": "Connection string detected. It may not be available when your app is migrated to Azure.\n\nReview and ensure it works from Azure. If you are connecting to a database, you might need to migrate the database to Azure. There are multiple ways to do it:\n    1. Migrate to Azure SQL Database for additional benefits (see the link below).\n    2. Consider Azure SQL Managed Instance if you need features that are not available in Azure SQL Database and you don\u2019t want to use a VM.\n    3. Migrate your database servers directly to SQL Server on Azure VMs.\n\nTo assess database migration effort, you can use Azure Migrate tool, see the link below.",
      "label": "Connection string is detected",
      "severity": "Potential",
      "effort": 3,
      "links": [
        {
          "title": "Migrate SQL Server database to Azure",
          "url": "https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?LinkID=2251731"
        },
        {
          "title": "Azure SQL Managed Instance",
          "url": "https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?LinkID=2251613"
        },
        {
          "title": "Azure Migrate",
          "url": "https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?linkid=2252410"
        }
      ]
    },
    "Logging.0102": {
      "id": "Logging.0102",
      "description": "Serilog logging framework detected. While Serilog is a popular logging framework, consider migrating to OpenTelemetry for better cloud-native observability and standardized telemetry. OpenTelemetry provides unified logging, metrics, and tracing with better Azure integration.",
      "label": "Serilog logging framework detected",
      "severity": "Optional",
      "effort": 3,
      "links": [
        {
          "title": "OpenTelemetry for .NET",
          "url": "https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?linkid=2330568"
        },
        {
          "title": "Migrate from Serilog to OpenTelemetry",
          "url": "https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?linkid=2330668"
        },
        {
          "title": "Azure Monitor OpenTelemetry",
          "url": "https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?linkid=2330569"
        }
      ]
    },
    "Local.0003": {
      "id": "Local.0003",
      "description": "Your application has local or network IO operations.\n\nIf you are targeting Managed Instance on Azure App Service, move persistent I/O to storage mounts (Azure Files/UNC). Keep local writes to temp only; connect to external dependencies via private endpoints/VNet to reduce latency.\n\nIO operations outside of the application folder might not be available on Azure App Service. Review and ensure IO APIs are attempting to access paths that will be available when your app is running on App Service sandbox. If you choose the containerized hosting option, your scenario still might be broken or have scalability issues.\n\nPossible solutions:\n    1. Files that the application needs can be deployed with the application or put in Azure Storage. You can use Azure Storage File Shares as a drop-in replacement for on-premises file share.\n    2. Other services that the application depends on might need to be migrated to Azure, this way you will get the benefit of lower latency in the cloud.\n    3. If your application needs to depend on services that run on-premise, you can connect your Azure and local networks with ExpressRoute, Hybrid Connections, or VPN solutions.",
      "label": "Local or network IO operations detected",
      "severity": "Potential",
      "effort": 3,
      "links": [
        {
          "title": "[Managed Instance] Storage mounts",
          "url": "https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?linkid=2346952"
        },
        {
          "title": "Azure file share",
          "url": "https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?LinkID=2242591"
        },
        {
          "title": "ExpressRoute",
          "url": "https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?LinkID=2250577"
        },
        {
          "title": "Hybrid Connections",
          "url": "https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?LinkID=2242588"
        },
        {
          "title": "Connect an on-prem network",
          "url": "https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?LinkID=2242591"
        },
        {
          "title": "Design to scale out",
          "url": "https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?linkid=2251007"
        }
      ]
    },
    "Local.0004": {
      "id": "Local.0004",
      "description": "Logging to local or network paths detected.\n\nIf you are targeting Managed Instance on Azure App Service, prefer Application Insights/App Service logging. If filesystem logs are required, write to a mounted Azure Files share configured via storage mounts and Key Vault secrets.\n\nLogging APIs that write to disk might not work on Azure App Service or Container.\n\nUse logging that stores logs in locations outside of the host unless its specifically required by your app. You can also use logging capabilities embedded in Azure, such as Azure App Service logging or Application Insights.\n\nFor migrating to AKS, use LogMonitor tool that can capture logs written to files, the console, or write logs and redirect them to Azure.",
      "label": "Logging to local or network paths detected",
      "severity": "Mandatory",
      "effort": 3,
      "links": [
        {
          "title": "[Managed Instance] Storage mounts",
          "url": "https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?linkid=2346952"
        },
        {
          "title": "Logging in Azure App Service",
          "url": "https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?LinkID=2251711"
        },
        {
          "title": "Logging in Application Insights",
          "url": "https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?LinkID=2251712"
        },
        {
          "title": "LogMonitor",
          "url": "https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?LinkID=2251308"
        }
      ]
    },
    "Local.0006": {
      "id": "Local.0006",
      "description": "Your application has hardcoded URLs that might correspond to services that are not accessible on Azure.\n\nReview and ensure that the application is attempting to access URLs that would be available from Azure. You might need to migrate those services to Azure too, this way you will get the benefit of lower latency in the cloud.\n\nIf your application needs to depend on services that run on-premises, you can connect your Azure and local networks with ExpressRoute, Hybrid Connections, or VPN solutions.",
      "label": "Hardcoded URLs detected",
      "severity": "Potential",
      "effort": 1,
      "links": [
        {
          "title": "ExpressRoute",
          "url": "https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?LinkID=2250577"
        },
        {
          "title": "Hybrid Connections",
          "url": "https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?LinkID=2242588"
        },
        {
          "title": "Connect an on-prem network",
          "url": "https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?LinkID=2242591"
        }
      ]
    },
    "Local.0007": {
      "id": "Local.0007",
      "description": "Local OS environment access detected.\n\nIf you are targeting Managed Instance on Azure App Service, Read config via App Settings or App Configuration; avoid machine\u2011specific environment APIs. Persist environment setup via install scripts when needed.\n\nWhen running in Azure App Service environment, your application can read environment variables that you define in App Service settings. Using environment API other than reading environment variables might indicate that your application depends on some local machine\u0027s features and might be broken on App Service sandbox or not scale well. Review your scenarios and either refactor them to be more cloud friendly or choose the option in App Service to host your application in the sandbox for Windows Container Web Apps.\n\nIf you choose to use other Azure hosting options such as Azure Container Apps (ACA) or Azure Kubernetes Service (AKS), environment APIs might work, however scaling still might be an issue.",
      "label": "Local OS environment access detected",
      "severity": "Potential",
      "effort": 1,
      "links": [
        {
          "title": "General App Service sandbox restrictions",
          "url": "https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?linkid=2250496"
        },
        {
          "title": "App Service sandbox for Windows Container Web Apps",
          "url": "https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?linkid=2251963"
        },
        {
          "title": "Design to scale out",
          "url": "https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?linkid=2251007"
        }
      ]
    },
    "Security.0103": {
      "id": "Security.0103",
      "description": "Certificate management packages or configurations detected. This may indicate the application is using local or custom certificate handling, which could require adjustments when migrating to Azure. Consider using Azure Key Vault Certificates for secure storage, lifecycle management, and integration with Azure services.",
      "label": "Certificate management dependency detected",
      "severity": "Potential",
      "effort": 5,
      "links": [
        {
          "title": "About Azure Key Vault certificates",
          "url": "https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?linkid=2335741"
        }
      ]
    },
    "Scale.0004": {
      "id": "Scale.0004",
      "description": "Potential duplex communication is detected.\n\nWebSockets work in most Azure environments and will not block migration. However, they need to be carefully reviewed to ensure the application will work correctly when it is scaled out.\n\nApplications may require a communication backplane if broadcasting a message from one scaled out instance should also broadcast that message from other instances. Similarly, it may be necessary to enable session affinity if it\u2019s required that users reconnect to the same server after a disconnect.\n\nSimilar issues could arise when server sent event streams are used (response content type \u0022text/event-stream\u0022).",
      "label": "Potential duplex communication is detected",
      "severity": "Optional",
      "effort": 3,
      "links": [
        {
          "title": "Design to scale out",
          "url": "https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?linkid=2250798"
        },
        {
          "title": "What is Azure SignalR Service?",
          "url": "https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?linkid=2251300"
        },
        {
          "title": "What is Azure Service Bus?",
          "url": "https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?linkid=2251301"
        }
      ]
    },
    "Security.0003": {
      "id": "Security.0003",
      "description": "Hardcoded sensitive data detected.\n\nIf you are targeting Managed Instance on Azure App Service, externalize secrets to Key Vault/App Configuration; use managed identity instead of passwords or embedded connection strings.\n\nWhile if targeting other Azure compute services:\n\nAvoid placing sensitive data such as passwords, ids, tokens etc., directly in config files and code since it compromises the security of your application.\n\nUse Azure App Configuration or Azure KeyVault to store secrets.",
      "label": "Hardcoded sensitive data detected",
      "severity": "Optional",
      "effort": 3,
      "links": [
        {
          "title": "Centralized app configuration and security",
          "url": "https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?LinkID=2250733"
        }
      ]
    },
    "SMTP.0001": {
      "id": "SMTP.0001",
      "description": "If you are targeting Managed Instance on Azure App Service, use an authenticated SMTP relay (e.g., SendGrid/Exchange Online). Store credentials in Key Vault; validate outbound restrictions for your subscription.\n\nWhile if targeting other Azure compute services, SMTP connections in your code might not work on Azure. Outbound email messages that are sent directly to external domains are made available only to certain subscription types. We recommend using authenticated SMTP relay services instead.",
      "label": "SMTP connections detected",
      "severity": "Potential",
      "effort": 3,
      "links": [
        {
          "title": "Troubleshoot SMTP problems",
          "url": "https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?LinkID=2243158"
        },
        {
          "title": "Set up emails with Microsoft 365 or Office 365",
          "url": "https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?LinkID=2249851"
        }
      ]
    },
    "Perf.0001": {
      "id": "Perf.0001",
      "description": "Synchronous API usage detected.\n\nUsing synchronous APIs can lead to more performance issues in Azure compared to on-premises environments due to different latency profiles. Consider adopting asynchronous code patterns.\n\nIn heavily loaded systems, especially where the I/O is substantial, using asynchronous patterns can improve overall throughput and performance. Asynchronous APIs enable a small pool of threads to manage thousands of concurrent requests without waiting on blocking calls. Instead of waiting for a long-running synchronous task to finish, the thread can handle another request. Conversely, numerous synchronous blocking calls can cause thread pool starvation and degrade response times.\n\nRefer to the links below to learn more about asynchronous programming.",
      "label": "Synchronous API usage detected",
      "severity": "Optional",
      "effort": 1,
      "links": [
        {
          "title": "Asynchronous programming",
          "url": "https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?linkid=2294824"
        },
        {
          "title": "ASP.NET Core Best Practices: avoid blocking calls",
          "url": "https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?linkid=2294727"
        }
      ]
    }
  }
}